                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CRICKET BRIEFS
                                                    Pawar to attend Lord rsquo;s   dinner  Mumbai: Board president Sharad Pawar is expected to attend the gala dinner to be hosted by former India captain Sunil Gavaskar at Lord rsquo;s on June 25 to celebrate the silver jubilee year of India rsquo;s World Cup triumph by Kapil rsquo;s Devils in 1983.
  ldquo;I have got an invitation but am not attending it. Mr Pawar will be attending it, rdquo; Board secretary Niranjan Shah said on Wednesday.   The gala dinner, which has been organised by the former captain and 1983 team member Gavaskar, is scheduled three days after the felicitation function by the Board to honour Kapil Dev and his teammates at New Delhi on Sunday.  ldquo;They (members of the 1983 World Cup winning squad) will be given cheques worth Rs 25 lakh each, rdquo; Shah said.   Steyn named SA rsquo;s best  Calcutta: South Africa pacer Dale Steyn won all the four awards he was nominated for including the prestigious Mutual amp; Federal SA Cricketer of the Year, at the fifth South Africa Cricket Awards ceremony in Durban on Tuesday night, says A Staff Reporter.  According to a CSA release, Steyn was also named the Castle Test Cricketer of the Year, SA Players rsquo; Player of the Year and the SuperSport Fans rsquo; Cricketer of the Year. Skipper Graeme Smith bagged the Standard Bank ODI Cricketer of the Year and Albie Morkel was named the Standard Bank International Pro20 Cricketer of the Year.  ICC rsquo;s nod   Karachi: The International Cricket Council (ICC) on Wednesday gave a thumbs up to Pakistan's preparations for the upcoming Champions Trophy and downplayed the security concerns of Australia, saying their fears were premature.  ICC president Ray Mali is heading a 14-member delegation, which took stock of the arrangements in Karachi, Lahore and Rawalpindi.   TNCA defence  Chennai: Tamil Nadu Cricket Association (TNCA) president N. Srinivasan on Wednesday refuted the charges of lsquo;inducements and bribery rsquo; levelled by former president A.C. Muthiah.  Addressing a press conference, Srinivasan said that it was rather unfortunate that Muthiah was lsquo;stooping to such low levels rsquo;. He alleged that lsquo;on the contrary, it is Muthiah and his team offering goodies and even jobs in their companies to lure the club members to vote for them rsquo;.  Sree case  Mumbai: The cricket board has sought details about the unsavoury happenings involving pacer Sreesanth two days ago at a Bangalore hotel where he is staying while taking part in a Board organised camp at the National Cricket Academy.
  ldquo;We have written to the hotel management and Sreesanth seeking details about what exactly happened there. He will stay there while attending the camp , rdquo; said BCCI chief administrative officer, Prof. Ratnakar Shetty on Wednesday. 
                                                                                                                                                               
